This is a personal summary of some highlights (especially cool OS/2 apps)
from David Barnes' awesome show at the OS/2 Bay Area User Group's meeting
on Monday (23 Jan).  (It was at the main auditorium of the Stanford Linear
Accelerator and was standing-room only.)

Btw, jokes and snide MS-bashing at the bottom. :-)  Cool OS/2 tips are in
the middle.

Oh, for those who don't know:  David is IBM's resident OS/2 nut-case.  He's
funnier than Letterman in a geek sort of a way; *highly* recommended if
you can catch him sometime.  He's starred in some of IBM's promotional
videos, I think, and maybe some of the TV commercials.

--Greg   [Note follow-ups.]

==============================================================================

Cool apps:
---------

 - TaskBar, $10 shareware.  This is kind of like a dynamic button-bar for
   currently running tasks (or a graphical version of the ctrl-esc task
   list).  It stays hidden until the mouse touches the bottom of the screen
   (configurable), at which point it pops up the scrollable button bar.
   Moving the mouse over the buttons pops up a little text thingy for each
   one (i.e., the name of the app), in case you can't remember which app
   goes with the telephone icon.  Sorry, I don't think he showed the company/
   author name (or if he did, I didn't write it down).

 - Back in a Flash (CCT, Inc).  He really liked this, and it did look pretty
   fast when backing up a small directory tree (with compression) from hard
   disk ("did I mention that it's 810MB?") to a PCMCIA non-volatile thingy.
   He also praised BakupWiz (which I've seen before).

 - formerly UniBeam (Binary Research), to become LinkWiz (PCX).  This is a
   Laplink-type app with very fast transfer speeds and OS/2, Windoze and DOS
   components.  He actually used it to transfer 15 or 20MB of goodies to
   one of the BAUG guys' ThinkPad at the end.  He spooged over this one.
   (Then again, he spooged over lots of stuff. :-) )  It should be out next
   month, I think.  (800) 800-4PCX or ftp.pcx.com.

 - ColorWorks for OS/2, v1.0 (SPG/Joel Krautheim, 305 362-6602).  *This*
   was a painfully cool app.  It's basically an image editor with lots of
   features and special effects, *plus* you get the ASCII parameters for
   the special effects (like emboss, blur, etc.) so you can create and save
   your own!  He didn't have time to show a lot, but all of his cool Warp
   BMP backgrounds were apparently made with this.  It does in-memory com-
   pression (so a 1MB image may take up only 100KB *while you work on it*)
   and has GOBS of multi-threading.  It does dithering and mapping to system
   colors like JoeView does.  It will be featured on Computer Chronicles,
   scheduled to air (at least in the SF Bay Area) on 28 February.  (Btw, the
   effects reminded me a lot of xv, for you Unix types out there.)

 - CPUmeter+ (Bon Ami).  Little bar graphs for each running app and the
   ability to kill them from a menu; looked pretty nice.

 - [Doom/2, not shown:  as I said previously, he claimed "it's just now what
    I'd call demoable"--this despite the fact that it was demoed two months
    ago.  Maybe that means its release is imminent?  Let's hope...]

 - MicroLearn Game Pack, vol. 2 (beta).  I wasn't clear on just how many of
   the games in his folder were from this pack, but the ones he showed looked
   *very* good--beautiful graphics, clean play.  One was called Combo/2, an
   update of Combo from volume 1 (rotate pipe fittings to keep moving balls
   from falling out or hitting bombs); one was a kind of super-Breakout
   game--which doesn't sound like much, but it looked pretty fun; one was
   an innovative update of the Trashman game; etc.  There was also one
   called Sauron which may or may not have been part of this.  I don't 
   think he demoed it, but its icon was definitely striking.  And I *think*
   it was the Game Pack which had a vertical notebook for something or 
   other, with gorgeous color icons on the tabs instead of text.  Lovely.

 - LA Gopher.  He only had time for a quick look at this, but it looked
   nice.  To be honest, though, I didn't see enough to know what the 
   differences might be from the IAK gopher client, except that the icon
   might have been slightly prettier.

 - VoiceType (IBM, $479).  Another just stupendously cool app, still cool
   even though I saw it demoed just a few months ago.  Basically you dictate
   to the computer, and it types it up for you.  The accuracy was incredibly
   good even with the noise in the auditorium, and he claimed 99% or even
   100% sometimes in his hotel room--better than 95% at all times.  This is
   a discrete-speech product, so you do have to talk - with - pauses - between
   - words.  But it's faster than it sounds.  Make sure you have at least
   12MB RAM and a 486/25 or better, btw.  Also, it controls the whole desktop,
   not just the dictation window.  You can say "Task list" "down" "enter"
   "file" "open" "paste" ... etc., and it will switch to the appropriate app,
   open a file and paste the clipboard contents into it (for example).  If
   it's got a menu entry, you can do it, and there are lots of shortcuts 
   available (e.g., "Desktop" "shutdown" "yes" or similar).  Nice.

 - SeamWin (The Chief?  Free?).  For those who still run Windoze apps, this
   is like FastLoad, but it works. :-)  It's just a stub program which runs
   in a seamless window and therefore keeps Win-OS2 loaded, so subsequent
   Win apps only start themselves, not all of Windoze.  (I've never used
   either and don't even have Windoze under Warp, so I don't know what the
   difficulties with FastLoad are.)

 - savedesk.cmd (free?).  Just a REXX script to save the state of your desktop
   so you can do a C-A-D reboot and not lose all of your icon positions (if
   you've moved them since last doing a real shutdown, that is).  Useful!

OK, that's all I have for demoed apps.  He's a great speaker, so it was 
hard to write stuff down--I kept paying attention. :-)  Apologies to the
authors of stuff mentioned above if I've screwed something up.

