Cool tips:
---------

A lot of these are probably in the "Stupid OS/2 Tricks" FAQ list, but <ahem>
I haven't read that yet. :-)

 - move a background window with the control key pressed:  window remains in
   the background

 - SET MENUSTYLE=SHORT in config.sys to get a less cluttered main desktop
   menu (most useful if you remember the ctrl/alt/shift key combos to make
   shadows and stuff with the mouse)

 - \os2\boot\altf1.cmd and altf1*.scr:  the scripts which control what
   happens when you do ALT-F1 at bootup to retrieve an archived version of
   your system files.  You can edit them so that you can switch between a
   LAN-enabled boot and an on-the-road boot, for example.

 - Create a folder called "system files" with shadows of config.sys, auto-
   exec.bat and (if applicable) the Windoze *.ini files.  Much easier to
   update things that way.

 - double click while the alt button is down:  settings notebook pops up

 - Launchpad settings has *three* pages.  You have to use the arrows at 
   the bottom (where first page says "page 1 of 2") to get to the middle
   page--no tab for it.

 - you can tear the drawers off of the Launchpad!  And I think it was a
   second-page setting which allows you to click on a drawer-icon and not
   have the drawer disappear.

 - HPFS:  don't have to do sysinstx to put OS2BOOT and OS2KRNL (or whatever
   they're called) in the right places--only on FAT.

 - Warp's disk-formatting is *fast* now.  5 seconds for an 810MB drive.
   ("Did I mention that my Thinkpad has an 810MB drive?")

 - if Windoze isn't coming up for some reason, go to a DOS full screen and
   start it as "win /b".  Then go look in \windows\bootload.txt to see how
   far it got and why it choked.

 - Windoze won't multitask if one of its menu items is highlighted!  This 
   is *not* an OS/2 bug--OS/2 is giving Windoze the timeslice, but Windoze
   doesn't give it to the app.  (IBM's modifications were principally limited
   to making Win run with OS/2 as the DPMI server.)  Watch out if you're doing
   one of those morph or raytrace things in the background...

 - If an app has gone bad and won't release control to the system:  do ctrl-
   esc, alt-esc, ctrl-esc, alt-esc several times--this is a higher-priority
   interrupt.

 - You can set up the Min Win Viewer to operate something like TaskBar (men-
   tioned above), albeit not with as much coolnitude.

 - US/Canadian folks can find a web page full of 800 numbers at
   http://att.net/dir800

